# P1-C03: Introduction to Computer Networks

## What is a Network?
- A system that lets two or more computing devices exchange data and share resources.
- Origin: driven by the need to **share expensive computing resources** (e.g., one central mainframe accessed by multiple terminals) — evolved into sharing files, printers, and remote information access.

---

## Core Components

| Component | Description |
|---|---|
| **Nodes** | Individual connected devices (computers, servers, smartphones, printers, routers, smart appliances). Each has a unique identifier. |
| **Links** | Communication pathways between nodes — physical (Ethernet, fiber) or wireless (Wi-Fi, cellular). Link speed/reliability/range affects performance. |
| **Packets** | Data broken into smaller chunks for transmission (like pages of a document, each addressed and numbered). |

### Packet Structure
- **Header** – source/destination addresses, sequence number, error-checking info.
- **Payload** – the actual data being sent.
- **Trailer (optional)** – additional error-checking info.

**Advantages of packets:**
- **Efficiency** – smaller packets interleave better with other data streams.
- **Robustness** – only lost/corrupted packets need retransmission, not the whole message.
- **Flexibility** – different data types can be sent simultaneously.

---

## Network Topologies (how nodes are arranged)

| Topology | Description | Pros | Cons |
|---|---|---|---|
| **Bus** | All nodes connect to one central cable (backbone); data broadcast to all, only intended recipient processes it | Simple, inexpensive | Whole network fails if backbone fails; hard to troubleshoot; degrades with more nodes |
| **Star** | All nodes connect to a central hub/switch | One failed link only affects that node; easy to add/remove nodes; easy to troubleshoot | Entire network down if hub/switch fails; more cabling needed |
| **Ring** | Nodes connected in a closed loop; data travels one direction | Handles high traffic well | One failed node/link breaks the whole ring; disruptive to add/remove nodes |
| **Mesh** | Every node connects to every other node | Highly reliable — alternate paths if one fails | Expensive and complex (many connections) |
| **Hybrid** | Combination of two+ topologies (most modern networks) | Balances cost, performance, reliability | — |

