## Reliability
- The probability that transmitted data arrives correctly, without errors.
- **Mechanisms:**
  - **Error detection/correction** – checksums/parity bits detect corruption; may trigger retransmission.
  - **Redundancy** – multiple paths (mesh) or backup hardware (routers/switches) ensure delivery even if one path fails.
  - **ACK/NACK** – Acknowledgement sent when a packet arrives successfully; Negative Acknowledgement or timeout triggers retransmission.

---

## Latency
- The delay/time for a packet to travel from source to destination.
- **Contributing factors:**
  - **Propagation Delay** – time for the signal to physically travel across the medium (limited by speed of light).
  - **Transmission Delay** – time to push all packet bits onto the link (depends on packet size & bandwidth).
  - **Processing Delay** – time for devices (routers) to examine headers and determine next hop.
  - **Queuing Delay** – time a packet waits in device queues before processing (varies with congestion).
- **Trade-off example:** Higher bandwidth reduces transmission delay, but heavy router congestion can still cause high latency via queuing delay.

