## Layered Model of Networking (Conceptual)
Networks are structured in layers — each layer serves the layer above and relies on the layer below (OSI model / TCP-IP model).

| Layer | Function |
|---|---|
| **Physical** | Raw transmission of bits over a medium (cables, radio); electrical/mechanical/procedural interfaces |
| **Data Link** | Transfers data between adjacent nodes on a single link; error detection/correction; physical (MAC) addressing |
| **Network** | Logical addressing (IP addresses); routes packets across multiple networks |
| **Transport** | End-to-end communication between applications; segmentation, reassembly, flow/error control (TCP, UDP operate here) |
| **Application** | Services directly to end-user apps (web browsing, email) |

---

## Protocols (Rules for Communication)

| Protocol | Layer | Description |
|---|---|---|
| **Ethernet** | Physical/Data Link | Defines data transmission over physical links in LANs; shared medium access |
| **IP (Internet Protocol)** | Network | Defines packet addressing (IP addresses) and routing |
| **TCP (Transmission Control Protocol)** | Transport | Connection-oriented; reliable, ordered, error-checked delivery (used for HTTP, FTP) |
| **UDP (User Datagram Protocol)** | Transport | Connectionless; faster but less reliable (used for streaming, gaming) |
| **HTTP (Hypertext Transfer Protocol)** | Application | Governs how browsers/servers exchange web data |

